    <h1>The Yoneda Lemma</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Bartosz Milewski · 2015 · <a href="https://bartoszmilewski.com/2015/09/01/the-yoneda-lemma/">Category Theory for Programmers, Ch. 14</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-10/">🍞 Ch10 (Natural Transformations)</a>, <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-13/">🍞 Ch13 (Representable Functors)</a>. 10 min.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none"><strong>Nat(Hom(a, &ndash;), F) &cong; F(a)</strong>. Natural transformations from a hom-functor to any functor F are in bijection with elements of F(a). An object is completely determined by its relationships to every other object. The entire natural transformation crystallizes from a single value: what you assign to the identity morphism.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. The hom-functor -->
    <h3>The hom-functor: an object seen from the outside</h3>
    <p>Fix an object <code>a</code> in a category. The <strong>hom-functor</strong> <code>Hom(a, &ndash;)</code> maps every object <code>x</code> to the set of morphisms from <code>a</code> to <code>x</code>. In Haskell, this is the <code>Reader a</code> functor: <code>Reader a x = a -&gt; x</code>. It captures everything <code>a</code> can "see" in the category.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; The hom-functor Hom(a, -) is the Reader functor.
; Reader a x = a -> x
; fmap f h = f . h   (post-compose)

(define (reader-fmap f h)
  (lambda (a) (f (h a))))

; Fix a = Int. Hom(Int, -) maps every type x
; to the set of functions Int -> x.
(define (square x) (* x x))
(define (show-int n) (string-append "val=" (number->string n)))

; fmap show-int over square : Int -> Int becomes Int -> String
(define square-then-show (reader-fmap show-int square))

(display (square-then-show 5)) (newline)
; "val=25" — post-compose show-int after square

(display (square-then-show 3))
; "val=9"
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Reader functor: fmap = post-compose
def reader_fmap(f, h):
    return lambda a: f(h(a))

square = lambda x: x * x
show_int = lambda n: f"val={n}"

square_then_show = reader_fmap(show_int, square)
print(square_then_show(5))  # val=25
print(square_then_show(3))  # val=9
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. The Yoneda bijection -->
    <h3>The Yoneda bijection: one value determines everything</h3>
    <p>A natural transformation <code>&alpha;</code> from <code>Hom(a, &ndash;)</code> to a functor <code>F</code> is a polymorphic function: for every <code>x</code>, it takes an <code>(a &rarr; x)</code> and returns an <code>F x</code>. The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoneda_lemma"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Yoneda lemma</a> says: every such natural transformation is determined by a single element of <code>F(a)</code>. To recover it, apply <code>&alpha;</code> to the identity morphism. To go the other way, take an element of <code>F(a)</code> and <code>fmap</code> any function over it.</p>

